      <p>In today's competitive job market, understanding how Applicant Tracking Systems (ATS) work is crucial for job seekers. With over 95% of Fortune 500 companies using ATS to screen resumes, your resume needs to be optimized to pass through these digital gatekeepers.</p>

      <h2>What is an ATS?</h2>
      <p>An Applicant Tracking System is software used by employers to collect, scan, and rank job applications. These systems help recruiters manage large volumes of applications by automatically filtering resumes based on specific criteria.</p>

      <h2>Key ATS Optimization Strategies</h2>

      <h3>1. Use Standard Formatting</h3>
      <p>Keep your resume format simple and clean. Avoid complex layouts, graphics, tables, and unusual fonts that can confuse ATS parsers.</p>

      <h3>2. Include Relevant Keywords</h3>
      <p>Carefully read job descriptions and incorporate relevant keywords and phrases naturally throughout your resume. Focus on:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Technical skills and certifications</li>
        <li>Industry-specific terminology</li>
        <li>Job titles and responsibilities</li>
        <li>Software and tools mentioned in the job posting</li>
